To connect your React contact form to a Hostinger database, you need to set up a "Backend" to handle the data. Since Hostinger Standard hosting runs on a **LAMP stack** (Linux, Apache, MySQL, PHP), the most efficient way is to use **PHP** as the bridge between your React App and the MySQL Database.

Here is the complete implementation plan.

### Step 1: Set up the Database (Hostinger Control Panel)

1.  Log in to Hostinger hPanel.
2.  Go to **Databases** -> **Management**.
3.  Create a new MySQL Database (e.g., name: `u123456789_promarch`, user: `u123456789_admin`, password: `YourStrongPassword`).
4.  Enter **phpMyAdmin**.
5.  Run this SQL query to create the table:

```sql
CREATE TABLE contact_messages (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    email VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    subject VARCHAR(255),
    message TEXT NOT NULL,
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
);
```

### Step 2: Create the Backend Scripts (PHP)

You need to create two files on your Hostinger server (inside `public_html`). You can do this via the Hostinger File Manager.

**1. `api/db_connect.php`** (Database Connection)
```php
<?php
// hostinger often uses 'localhost', but check your dashboard
$host = "localhost"; 
$user = "u123456789_admin"; // YOUR DATABASE USERNAME
$pass = "YourStrongPassword"; // YOUR DATABASE PASSWORD
$dbname = "u123456789_promarch"; // YOUR DATABASE NAME

try {
    $conn = new PDO("mysql:host=$host;dbname=$dbname", $user, $pass);
    $conn->setAttribute(PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE, PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION);
} catch(PDOException $e) {
    die(json_encode(["error" => "Connection failed: " . $e->getMessage()]));
}
?>
```

**2. `api/submit_contact.php`** (The API Endpoint)
```php
<?php
header("Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *"); // Allow React app to access
header("Access-Control-Allow-Headers: Content-Type");
header("Content-Type: application/json");

include 'db_connect.php';

// Get JSON data from React
$data = json_decode(file_get_contents("php://input"));

if($data) {
    $name = htmlspecialchars(strip_tags($data->name));
    $email = htmlspecialchars(strip_tags($data->email));
    $subject = htmlspecialchars(strip_tags($data->subject));
    $message = htmlspecialchars(strip_tags($data->message));

    $query = "INSERT INTO contact_messages (name, email, subject, message) VALUES (:name, :email, :subject, :message)";
    $stmt = $conn->prepare($query);

    // Bind parameters
    $stmt->bindParam(':name', $name);
    $stmt->bindParam(':email', $email);
    $stmt->bindParam(':subject', $subject);
    $stmt->bindParam(':message', $message);

    if($stmt->execute()) {
        echo json_encode(["message" => "Success"]);
    } else {
        echo json_encode(["error" => "Failed to save data"]);
    }
} else {
    echo json_encode(["error" => "No data received"]);
}
?>
```

### Step 3: Visualize Data (Simple Admin Viewer)

Create **`view_messages.php`** in your `public_html` folder to see the data.

```php
<?php
include 'api/db_connect.php'; // Reuse connection
$stmt = $conn->prepare("SELECT * FROM contact_messages ORDER BY created_at DESC");
$stmt->execute();
$messages = $stmt->fetchAll(PDO::FETCH_ASSOC);
?>
<!-- Simple HTML Table to view data -->
<style>table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-family: sans-serif; } th, td { border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; } th { background-color: #00459c; color: white; }</style>
<h2>Contact Form Submissions</h2>
<table>
    <tr><th>Date</th><th>Name</th><th>Email</th><th>Subject</th><th>Message</th></tr>
    <?php foreach($messages as $msg): ?>
    <tr>
        <td><?php echo $msg['created_at']; ?></td>
        <td><?php echo $msg['name']; ?></td>
        <td><?php echo $msg['email']; ?></td>
        <td><?php echo $msg['subject']; ?></td>
        <td><?php echo $msg['message']; ?></td>
    </tr>
    <?php endforeach; ?>
</table>
```

### Step 4: Update React Application

I will now update your `pages/Contact.tsx` to send data to this PHP endpoint instead of showing an alert.

**Note:** In the code below, replace `https://your-domain.com/api/submit_contact.php` with your actual website URL where you uploaded the PHP files.

